  aLinguistic knowledge consists of a structured set of form-meaning pairs (constructions), which one can conceptualize as a network or “constructicon.” The essays in this volume engage in a theoretical and empirical exploration of different aspects of such a “constructicon.” The book is addressed to a sophisticated audience and to those readers interested in construction grammar and usage-based descriptive approaches.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aConstruction grammarvCongresses. 0aEnglish languagexGrammarvCongresses. 0aGerman languagexGrammarvCongresses. 4aKonstruktionsgrammatik. 4aSprachtheorie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Grammar & Punctuation.2bisacsh  aConstruction Grammar.  aTheory of Language.1 aBallmer, Sinja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoas, Hans C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBudde, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBücker, Jörg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Knop, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiedrichsen, Elke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Kerstin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFroschauer, Regine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLasch, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLasch, Alexander, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMichel, Sascha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsswald, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichter, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRostila, Joun